"use strict";(self.webpackChunk_N_E=self.webpackChunk_N_E||[]).push([[4283],{74283:function(e){e.exports=JSON.parse('[{"id":"q1","category":"Theory","question":"The Caching spec uses `Cache-Control: max-age=31536000, immutable` for JS/CSS bundles but `Cache-Control: no-cache` for HTML files. Why can bundles use a 1-year cache while HTML cannot?","options":["JavaScript files are smaller than HTML and safer to cache longer without consuming CDN storage","Content-hashed filenames change whenever file content changes — a new deploy produces a new URL (app.3f2c1a.js → app.9b7d2e.js), making the cached old file harmless. HTML files reference the current bundle URL and must always be fresh to point users to the latest assets","Browsers automatically invalidate JS cache on page reload but not HTML","CDNs apply extended TTLs to JS files automatically regardless of Cache-Control directives"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec documents: \'Static assets with content-hash filenames\' and Cache-Control values per resource type. Content addressing makes long-lived caching safe: `app.3f2c1a.js` and `app.9b7d2e.js` are different URLs — no invalidation needed. The HTML is the \'entry point\' that references the current bundle URL. If HTML is cached for a year, users would run old code for a year after a deploy. `no-cache` means \'check with the server on every visit but use the cached version if it hasn\'t changed (304 Not Modified)\' — fast and always current.","hint":"If the file\'s URL changes every time its content changes, can an old cached URL ever serve stale content for that specific URL?"},{"id":"q2","category":"Theory","question":"The Caching hierarchy diagram shows 6 layers: Browser → CDN → API Gateway → Redis → Read Replica → Primary DB. After a POST request updates a user\'s profile in the Primary DB, which caches must be proactively invalidated and why?","options":["Only the Redis cache needs invalidation — CDN and browser caches expire via TTL naturally","Only the CDN edge cache needs purging via a cache invalidation API call","Redis must be invalidated immediately on write (otherwise subsequent API requests serve stale data). CDN must then be purged or tag-invalidated (otherwise edge nodes serve the old API response for the CDN TTL duration). Browser cache expires naturally via TTL — proactive invalidation is impractical","All 6 cache layers self-invalidate via event-driven webhooks registered at startup"],"correct":2,"explanation":"The spec documents write-through and cache-aside invalidation patterns. On a profile update: (1) Write to Primary DB, (2) `redis.del(\'user:${userId}\')` — immediate invalidation so the next API request fetches fresh data and repopulates Redis, (3) CDN purge via API (Cloudflare, CloudFront) for any edge-cached API responses. Browser caches: the spec sets `Cache-Control: no-store` for authenticated API responses, so browsers don\'t cache user-specific data. The checklist: \'Cache invalidation for all writes.\'","hint":"After a write, which caches will serve stale data on the next request? Which ones can you programmatically tell to refresh?"},{"id":"q3","category":"Practical","question":"What critical bug will cause stale data to persist indefinitely in production?","code":"async function getUserProfile(userId: string) {\\n  const cacheKey = `user:profile:${userId}`;\\n  \\n  // Check cache first\\n  const cached = await redis.get(cacheKey);\\n  if (cached) return JSON.parse(cached);\\n  \\n  // Cache miss - fetch from database\\n  const user = await db.query(\\n    \'SELECT id, name, email, role FROM users WHERE id = $1\',\\n    [userId]\\n  );\\n  \\n  // Backfill cache\\n  await redis.set(cacheKey, JSON.stringify(user.rows[0]));\\n  //              ^ No TTL specified!\\n  \\n  return user.rows[0];\\n}","codeLanguage":"typescript","options":["`JSON.parse` is called on the cached string but `JSON.stringify` was not called before storing","The cache key `user:profile:${userId}` should use a hash function to prevent key length issues","No TTL is set on the Redis key — if the user updates their profile, the cached version is never refreshed (persists until Redis restart or memory pressure evicts it). Fix: `redis.setex(cacheKey, 300, JSON.stringify(user.rows[0]))` for a 5-minute TTL","The function should use `redis.mget` to batch multiple user lookups for efficiency"],"correct":2,"explanation":"The spec documents TTL values per data type: user profile = 300s (5 minutes). Redis without TTL means: a user changes their name, the old name stays in cache until the server restarts or Redis evicts it due to memory pressure (`allkeys-lru`). The checklist mandates: \'TTL values based on data change frequency\' and \'Cache invalidation for all writes.\' Fix: either `SETEX` with TTL, or delete the cache key when the profile is updated (write-invalidation pattern). Both are in the spec.","hint":"If you set a Redis key without an expiry and the underlying data changes, when does the cached value ever get refreshed?"},{"id":"q4","category":"Practical","question":"A viral post causes 50,000 req/s to hit the same cache key. The TTL expires at that moment — all 50,000 requests find a cache miss and query the database simultaneously. What is this problem called and what is the spec\'s solution?","options":["Cache poisoning — prevented by validating all cache key inputs against an allowlist","Cache stampede (thundering herd) — prevented by using a distributed lock: `SET cache_lock NX EX 5` so only ONE process rebuilds the cache while others wait or serve a slightly stale value using early expiration","Cache fragmentation — prevented by increasing Redis `maxmemory` allocation","Cache avalanche — prevented by adding jitter to TTL values (TTL \xb1 random 30%)"],"correct":1,"explanation":"The spec documents cache stampede and the `SET NX EX 5` (set if not exists, 5s expiry) distributed lock solution. When TTL expires: the first request acquires the lock and rebuilds the cache; subsequent requests check for the lock, find it taken, and either: (a) serve a slightly stale value using early expiration (refresh 30s before expiry), or (b) wait and retry. Only 1 database query fires instead of 50,000. The spec also documents \'early expiration refresh: trigger at 30s before expiry\' as a proactive prevention strategy for hot keys.","hint":"When thousands of requests all find the same cache miss at the same moment, how do you ensure only one of them queries the database?"},{"id":"q5","category":"Theory","question":"According to the Caching Production Checklist, what Redis eviction policy should be configured and what cache hit rate target indicates a well-optimized cache?","options":["`volatile-lru` eviction; >50% hit rate target","`noeviction` policy; >90% hit rate — never evict cached items to maintain data integrity","`allkeys-lru` eviction policy; >80% hit rate — LRU evicts the least recently used keys when memory fills, preserving hot data. Below 80% hit rate, cache overhead may outweigh benefits and TTL/key strategy needs review","`allkeys-random` eviction; >60% hit rate target"],"correct":2,"explanation":"The spec mandates `Redis maxmemory-policy: allkeys-lru` and cache hit rate monitoring. `allkeys-lru`: when Redis reaches `maxmemory`, evict the least recently accessed key from ALL keys (not just those with TTL). This preserves hot/frequently-accessed data. `noeviction` returns errors when memory is full — unacceptable in production. `volatile-lru` only evicts keys with TTL set — keys without TTL never evict, risking memory overflow. The >80% hit rate target: below this, frequent cache misses mean the cache isn\'t preventing many DB queries — review which data to cache and TTL lengths.","hint":"When Redis runs out of memory, what should happen? Should it error, evict random keys, or intelligently keep the most recently accessed data?"}]')}}]);